Addressing the problem of climate change using Java or any programming language typically involves developing applications, tools, and systems that help reduce carbon emissions, enhance energy efficiency, and promote sustainable practices. In the context of transportation systems, some strategies to consider are:

1. Transportation route optimization: Develop algorithms that find the most efficient routes for vehicles, thus reducing fuel consumption and emissions.
2. Smart traffic management: Create systems that monitor traffic and adjust signals, road usage, and public transportation to minimize congestion and pollution.
3. Public transport planning: Develop tools to analyze and improve public transportation networks, making them more efficient, reliable, and eco-friendly.
4. Electric vehicle (EV) infrastructure: Create applications that facilitate the management of EV charging stations and the integration of renewable energy sources.
5. Eco-driving systems: Develop systems that provide real-time feedback to drivers regarding their driving habits, helping them adopt more fuel-efficient behaviors.

Here's an example of a simplified Java code that generates optimized routes for vehicles using the Dijkstra's shortest path algorithm. In reality, more sophisticated optimization algorithms would be used, and the code would integrate with existing transportation systems:

```java
import java.util.*;

class Graph {
    private int vertices;
    private LinkedList<Edge>[] adjacencyList;

    Graph(int vertices) {
        this.vertices = vertices;
        adjacencyList = new LinkedList[vertices];
        for (int i = 0; i < vertices; i++) {
            adjacencyList[i] = new LinkedList<>();
        }
    }

    void addEdge(int source, int destination, int weight) {
        Edge edge = new Edge(source, destination, weight);
        adjacencyList[source].addFirst(edge);
    }

    void calculateShortestPath(int source) {
        boolean[] visited = new boolean[vertices];
        int[] distances = new int[vertices];

        PriorityQueue<Edge> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(vertices, new Edge());

        for (int i = 1; i < vertices; i++) {
            distances[i] = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        }

        pq.add(new Edge(source, source, 0));
        distances[source] = 0;

        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
            int currentNode = pq.remove().destination;
            if (!visited[currentNode]) {
                visited[currentNode] = true;
                LinkedList<Edge> edges = adjacencyList[currentNode];
                for (Edge edge : edges) {
                    int destination = edge.destination;
                    int newDistance = distances[currentNode] + edge.weight;
                    if (distances[destination] > newDistance) {
                        pq.add(new Edge(currentNode, destination, newDistance));
                        distances[destination] = newDistance;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        printShortestPath(distances);
    }

    void printShortestPath(int[] distances) {
        System.out.println("Optimized routes from Source to Destination:");
        for (int i = 1; i < distances.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Source -> Destination (" + i + ") : " + distances[i] + " units");
        }
    }

    static class Edge implements Comparator<Edge> {
        int source;
        int destination;
        int weight;

        Edge() {}

        Edge(int source, int destination, int weight) {
            this.source = source;
            this.destination = destination;
            this.weight = weight;
        }

        @Override
        public int compare(Edge e1, Edge e2) {
            return Integer.compare(e1.weight, e2.weight);
        }
    }
}

public class RouteOptimization {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int vertices = 6;
        Graph graph = new Graph(vertices);
        graph.addEdge(1, 2, 2);
        graph.addEdge(1, 4, 1);
        graph.addEdge(2, 3, 4);
        graph.addEdge(2, 5, 3);
        graph.addEdge(4, 2, 1);
        graph.addEdge(4, 5, 5);
        graph.addEdge(5, 3, 2);

        int source = 1;
        graph.calculateShortestPath(source);
    }
}
```

This code calculates the shortest path from a source to other destinations. It should be adapted to use real-world data and, as previously mentioned, can be integrated into existing transportation infrastructure to optimize routes, reduce fuel consumption, and ultimately decrease carbon emissions.

