For creating a small .NET microservice that sends emails through SMTP and is consumed by other services using gRPC, follow the steps below.

Step 1: Create the Email Service using .NET and gRPC
1. Create a new .NET gRPC Service by running the following command in your terminal or command prompt:
```
dotnet new grpc -o EmailService
```
2. Add `MailKit` NuGet package to your project `EmailService.csproj` for handling email sending via SMTP:
```
<PackageReference Include="MailKit" Version="2.15.0" />
```
3. Define a "SendEmail" service in the `Protos\emailservice.proto`:
```proto
syntax = "proto3";

option csharp_namespace = "EmailService";

package emailservice;

service Email {
  rpc Send (EmailRequest) returns (EmailResponse);
}

message EmailRequest {
  string from = 1;
  string to = 2;
  string subject = 3;
  string body = 4;
}

message EmailResponse {
  bool success = 1;
  string message = 2;
}
```
4. Implement the `Email` service in the `Services\EmailService.cs`:
```csharp
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Grpc.Core;
using EmailService;
using MailKit.Net.Smtp;
using MimeKit;

public class EmailSenderService : Email.EmailBase
{
    public override async Task<EmailResponse> Send(EmailRequest request, ServerCallContext context)
    {
        var message = new MimeMessage();
        message.From.Add(new MailboxAddress(request.From));
        message.To.Add(new MailboxAddress(request.To));
        message.Subject = request.Subject;

        message.Body = new TextPart("plain") { Text = request.Body };

        try
        {
            using var client = new SmtpClient();
            await client.ConnectAsync("smtp.example.com", 587, false);
            client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove("XOAUTH2"); // Disabling XOAUTH2 for testing purposes
            await client.AuthenticateAsync("username", "password");
            await client.SendAsync(message);
            await client.DisconnectAsync(true);
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            return new EmailResponse { Success = false, Message = ex.Message };
        }

        return new EmailResponse { Success = true, Message = "Email sent successfully" };
    }
}
```
Replace `"smtp.example.com"`, `"username"`, and `"password"` with your SMTP credentials.

Step 2: Consume the Email Service from another .NET service
1. Create a new .NET Console project by running the following command:
```
dotnet new console -o EmailConsumer
```
2. Add gRPC-generated code from your `EmailService`.
3. Add the NuGet packages `Google.Protobuf`, `Grpc.Net.Client`, and `Grpc.Tools` to your project's `EmailConsumer.csproj`:
```xml
<PackageReference Include="Google.Protobuf" Version="3.19.1" />
<PackageReference Include="Grpc.Net.Client" Version="2.41.0" />
<PackageReference Include="Grpc.Tools" Version="2.41.0" PrivateAssets="All" />
```
4. Consume the gRPC Email service from your `EmailConsumer` project by using the following code in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using EmailService;
using Grpc.Core;
using Grpc.Net.Client;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main()
    {
        var channel = GrpcChannel.ForAddress("https://localhost:5001"); // Replace with the actual email service address
        var client = new Email.EmailClient(channel);

        var emailRequest = new EmailRequest
        {
            From = "youremail@example.com",
            To = "recipient@example.com",
            Subject = "Test email",
            Body = "This is a test email sent using gRPC."
        };

        var response = await client.SendAsync(emailRequest);

        if (response.Success)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Email sent successfully!");
        }
        else
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Error sending email: {response.Message}");
        }
    }
}
```
Replace `https://localhost:5001` with the actual EmailService's address.

Now, you have created a small .NET microservice to send emails through SMTP and consumed it using gRPC. Make sure to run both the EmailService and EmailConsumer projects to test your implementation.

